04128nam a22005415i 9780520914995DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209149957 a10.1525/97805209149952doi  a(DE-B1597)649013  a(OCoLC)1194909545  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0041302bisacsh1 aErickson, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRewriting Shakespeare, Rewriting Ourselves /cPeter Erickson; ed. by Peter Erickson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: CRITICAL LOCATIONS -- tPART ONE. SHAKESPEARE'S REPRESENTATIONS OF WOMEN -- t1 Female Rule, Patriarchal Ideology -- t2 Refracted Images of Queen Elizabeth in Venus and Adonis and The Rape of Lucrece -- t3 The Political Effects of Gender and Class in All's Well That Ends Well -- t4 Gender, Genre, and Nation in Hamlet -- tPART TWO WOMEN WRITERS' REPRESENTATIONS OF SHAKESPEARE -- t5 Some Versions of Tradition -- t6 Shakespeare, Angelou, Cheney: The Administration of the Humanities in the Reagan-Bush Era -- t7 Shakespeare's Changing Status in the Novels of Gloria Naylor -- t8 Adrienne Rich's Re-Vision of Shakespeare -- tAfterword: Identity Politics, Multicultural Society -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aParticipants in the current debate about the literary canon generally separate the established literary order—of which Shakespeare is the most visible icon—from the emergent minority literatures. In this challenging study, Peter Erickson insists on bringing the two realms together. He asks: what impact does a revision of the literary canon have on Shakespeare's status?Part One of his book is about Shakespeare on women. In analyses of several Shakespearean works, Erickson discusses Shakespeare's ambivalence about women as a reflection of male anxiety about the cultural authority of Queen Elizabeth. Part Two is about (contemporary) women on Shakespeare. Erickson discusses Adrienne Rich's revision of the very concept of canon and discusses how several African-American women writers (in particular Maya Angelou and Gloria Naylor) have reflected on the ambivalent status of Shakespeare in their worlds.Erickson here offers a model for multicultural literary criticism and a new conceptual framework with which to discuss issues of identity politics. Rewriting Shakespeare, Rewriting Ourselves makes an important contribution to the national debate about educational policy in the humanities.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEuropean. 4aGeneral. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh1 aErickson, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008646340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091499540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914995/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles